{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/blog/git-getting-started","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"excerpt":"Here is a simple way to understand Git for first-timers. Learning Git is easy when Git is your first version control tool. But it becomes aâ€¦","html":"<p>Here is a simple way to understand Git for first-timers.</p>\n<p>Learning Git is easy when Git is your first version control tool. But it becomes a little difficult for somebody who is already aware of other version control tools like SVN, Perforce, or TFS.</p>\n<p>Why is that it is difficult to understand Git? This because Git totally inverts the way we handle branches. Now you need to unlearn and re-learn this new thing. And, I know it is a little painful ðŸ’‰</p>\n<p>The intension of this blog is to make this journey a little painless.</p>\n<h2 id=\"So-what-is-Git\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#So-what-is-Git\" aria-label=\"So what is Git permalink\" class=\"gatsby-remark-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>So what is Git?</h2>\n<p>It is a Distributed Version Control System. Or, in simple words you use Git to checkin code.</p>\n<p>However, Git can also be used to store other digital information. I use Git to store eBooks, Notes, PDFs, sketch notes and sometimes even data (For AI &#x26; ML)</p>\n<h2 id=\"Why-Git-Why-not-continue-to-use-the-others\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#Why-Git-Why-not-continue-to-use-the-others\" aria-label=\"Why Git Why not continue to use the others permalink\" class=\"gatsby-remark-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Why Git? Why not continue to use the others?</h2>\n<p>Git is famous among Open source software development community and now almost every commercial software entity uses Git.</p>\n<p>Why does majority of organisations use Git? Because it save a lot of time in branching and merging. Let me tell you a story of mine. Long ago when I started as a fresher. We used Tortoise SVN as a source control tool. I was given the job of merging and branching at the begining of every sprint. And it used to take good two days to branch and merge three source control repository.</p>\n<p>The organisation wanted to be more agile so they had to introduce Git. Git hardly takes few minutes to branch and merge.This was one of the reasons organisations embraced Git.</p>\n<h2 id=\"How-to-use-Git\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#How-to-use-Git\" aria-label=\"How to use Git permalink\" class=\"gatsby-remark-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>How to use Git?</h2>\n<p>We start with commands while learn Git. Git commands are great. However, it is not the best way to understand Git.</p>\n<p>Even <a href=\"https://xkcd.com/\">XKCD</a> has commented on how difficult (yet amazing) the product is.</p>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 330px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/d28f46654cd788d9c8e29a04bf1bf2f2/d9ecf/xkcd-git.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 144.5945945945946%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Difficult and amazing Git\"\n        title=\"Difficult and amazing Git\"\n        src=\"/static/d28f46654cd788d9c8e29a04bf1bf2f2/d9ecf/xkcd-git.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/d28f46654cd788d9c8e29a04bf1bf2f2/12f09/xkcd-git.png 148w,\n/static/d28f46654cd788d9c8e29a04bf1bf2f2/e4a3f/xkcd-git.png 295w,\n/static/d28f46654cd788d9c8e29a04bf1bf2f2/d9ecf/xkcd-git.png 330w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 330px) 100vw, 330px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Difficult and amazing Git</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<h2 id=\"So-how-do-we-go-about-learning-Git\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#So-how-do-we-go-about-learning-Git\" aria-label=\"So how do we go about learning Git permalink\" class=\"gatsby-remark-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>So how do we go about learning Git</h2>\n<p>We need to understand Git theoritically first. More importantly we gotta visualize how branching and merging happens in Git.</p>\n<p>Below is the aproach that has worked for me</p>\n<p>Things to do before you start</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Install Visual Studio Code and create a Github repository (You can also use BitBicket, Azure Devops or any other source control site)</li>\n<li>Try creating a branch from Visual Studio Code. Refer any Youtube video to do this</li>\n<li>Here is an important step. We need visualize what is happening with each command. So we use the repo visualization tool <a href=\"https://github.com/FredrikNoren/ungit\">Ungit</a>{:target=\"<em>blank\"}. There is a nice <a href=\"https://youtu.be/hkBVAi3oKvo\">video</a>{:target=\"</em>blank\"}  about Ungit.</li>\n<li>There is an extension for Ungit in Visual Studio Code. Install and see the magic. It visualizes Git operations. Now try creating a new branch and merge it into main branch using Visual Studio Code.</li>\n<li>Now open git <a href=\"https://github.github.com/training-kit/\">cheat sheet</a>{:target=\"_blank\"} and try to understand the commands</li>\n</ol>\n<p><figure class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figure\" style=\"\">\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 590px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/e8d30b1c220cde485cdcc1190e8c41f4/71d2f/learn-git-branching.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 62.83783783783784%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Learn Git branching\"\n        title=\"Learn Git branching\"\n        src=\"/static/e8d30b1c220cde485cdcc1190e8c41f4/fcda8/learn-git-branching.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/e8d30b1c220cde485cdcc1190e8c41f4/12f09/learn-git-branching.png 148w,\n/static/e8d30b1c220cde485cdcc1190e8c41f4/e4a3f/learn-git-branching.png 295w,\n/static/e8d30b1c220cde485cdcc1190e8c41f4/fcda8/learn-git-branching.png 590w,\n/static/e8d30b1c220cde485cdcc1190e8c41f4/efc66/learn-git-branching.png 885w,\n/static/e8d30b1c220cde485cdcc1190e8c41f4/c83ae/learn-git-branching.png 1180w,\n/static/e8d30b1c220cde485cdcc1190e8c41f4/71d2f/learn-git-branching.png 1485w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span>\n    <figcaption class=\"gatsby-resp-image-figcaption\">Learn Git branching</figcaption>\n  </figure></p>\n<p>Git packages also come with IDEs like Visual Studio or VS Code. So you can use Git directly inside these IDEs as well.</p>\n<h2 id=\"Final-opinion\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#Final-opinion\" aria-label=\"Final opinion permalink\" class=\"gatsby-remark-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Final opinion</h2>\n<p>It took me some time to learn and understand the nuances of Git. But by using this method I retained what I learned for a really long time. This indeed is very important.</p>\n<h3 id=\"Other-tools-worthy-of-a-mention\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#Other-tools-worthy-of-a-mention\" aria-label=\"Other tools worthy of a mention permalink\" class=\"gatsby-remark-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Other tools worthy of a mention</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Branching is the most important concept of Git. Branching can be visualized using the branch <a href=\"https://learngitbranching.js.org/\">visualization online tool</a>{:target=\"_blank\"}. Go ahead and play here for few minutes (You may skip this if you feel you are confident of using Git)</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://git-scm.com/download/gui/win\">https://git-scm.com/download/gui/win</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://git-school.github.io/visualizing-git/\">http://git-school.github.io/visualizing-git/</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"References\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#References\" aria-label=\"References permalink\" class=\"gatsby-remark-autolink before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>References</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://trends.google.com/trends/explore?date=all&#x26;geo=US&#x26;q=git,svn\">Google trends</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://softwareengineering.stackexchange.com/questions/136079/are-there-any-statistics-that-show-the-popularity-of-git-versus-svn\">Stack exchange</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://xkcd.com/\">XKCD</a></li>\n</ul>","timeToRead":3,"id":"5f1754c0-5d8e-5834-8327-fa7585d22a97","frontmatter":{"date":"April 14, 2020","title":"Git - Getting started"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/blog/git-getting-started"}},"staticQueryHashes":["1033876704","3435786681","550521386"]}